^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|For those not familiar with the rule of 15, it works as follows. If your HCP plus spades are 15 or more, you should open in 4th seat. For example, you would open a 10 HCP hand with 5 spades (10 + 5 = 15) or an 11 HCP hand with 4 spades. The idea here is, particularly with weaker openings, this gives you some protection of the opponents not being to out compete you in spades.|
PG| ***** 459 ***** |


AT|

I am not a big fan of the rule of 15. I don't think it has a sound theoretical basis. My style is to open hands in 4th seat that meet the rule of 20, regardless of my spade holding, and not open hands that do not meet the rule of 20. If I have a marginal rule of 20 opener with weak majors, very occasionally I might choose to pass for tactical reasons (especially if I am vul and they are not) -- the opponents might outbid me in a major. But that is rare -- as you know, I hate to pass. :)|
PG| ***** 460 ***** |


AT|

And if you choose to play the rule of 15, I suggest you still open all rule of 20 hands. For example, if I had a spade void, I certainly would open any hands with 11-14 HCP even though they do not meet the rule of 15.|
